>It’s been a year or thereabout since you’ve found yourself in this strange world of up-right walking animals, and nearly half a year since you started dating Tamasa, a fox anthro.
>She's barely 4’10, but the sheer amount of spunk she has would make one think she’s 10 feet tall.
>Right now, though, she looks like a kicked puppy. Or maybe a kicked kit is more appropriate considering her species.
>“Anon…” She shakes her head slowly, as if unable to believe what you just told her. “That’s not funny.”
>You look away, try to think of what to say. Your eyes fall to the boxy TV you and Tam were watching a moment ago.
>Despite the multitude of species living on this odd, parallel dimension earth, there’s been notably less conflict in the world history of the anthros, and as such, societal development is all over the place. It’s 2061 on the anthro calendar, yet Tam’s TV would look right at home in a 90s household back on earth.
>Now that you think about it, it’s obvious why there’s been so much less conflict here than on earth. There is one aspect where anthros outpace humanity to such a degree that it’s not funny.
>And that aspect is emotional intelligence.
>“Anon?”
You turn back to Tam’s horrified visage and give her an awkward smile. “Ah, no, it’s not funny, is it?” you say, forcing a laugh and kicking yourself for not being more tactful.
